Hello Deena,
It does not necessarily mean that a spammer has gained access to
personal e-mail addresses but has gained access to the group address.
Simply by addressing a mail to the group gets it delivered to each and
every member.

You are quite right that being public or private makes no
difference to any protection you may have if the wrong person gets
hold of a group address. The only resource, as you suggest, would be
to block the address from which the junk comes.

Our group is a work based group and occasionally have the
situation where a member becomes a supervisor and no longer needs
membership of the group but may, conceivably, need to contact everyone
at some time about something. They are told that there is nothing to
stop them using the group address even though they are no longer
members and it will be delivered to each and every current member. The
differences being it will not show up in the website and the sender
will not receive a copy of the message.

I think it would be a help if the groups programme could be set so
that the address of a message received into the group could be
compared against the list of current members and if found not to be
listed then not forwarded on. Maybe this could be made an optional
choice.

Reg

